yer_embedded\n\nIACT workshops are <em>collaborative environments</em> offering exciting 	    experiences for <em>business leaders, academics, and clinicians</em> within 	    the health care industry that will lead to tomorrow\'s <em>actionable solutions</em>.','Discover IACT!','','publish','open','open','','discover-iact','','','2010-12-30 23:37:36','2010-12-30 23:37:36','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=33',0,'post','',0),(43,2,'2010-12-30 23:48:38','2010-12-30 23:48:38','The IACT kick-off event was a tremendous success thanks to all of the wonderful, 			passionate attendees! Your dedication and commitment to improving Pittsburgh and 			healthcare were inspiring. All 50+ people who attended were instrumental to IACT\'s 			success and we sincerely hope to see everyone at future IACT events!\n\nResults from the event have been posted! See them <em><a href=\"aging\">here</a></em>.','See Innovation Concepts from the IACT Kickoff Event!','','publish','open','open','','see-innovation-concepts-from-the-iact-kickoff-event-2','','','2010-12-30 23:48:38','2010-12-30 23:48:38','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=43',0,'post','',0),(46,2,'2010-12-30 23:49:59','2010-12-30 23:49:59','The IACT Innovator\'s Challenge is fast approaching and applications are now open!             Spend an exhilarating day learning from experienced professionals and competing with             colleagues from the University of Pittsburgh and Carnegie Mellon.\n\nFor more information head on over to the             <em><a href=\"http://iactpgh.com/challenge\">IACT Innovator\'s Challenge</a></em>.','IACT Innovator’s Challenge','','publish','open','open','','iact-innovators-challenge-2','','','2010-12-30 23:49:59','2010-12-30 23:49:59','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=46',0,'post','',0),(62,2,'2010-12-31 00:37:49','2010-12-31 00:37:49','','Home','','publish','open','open','','home','','','2010-12-31 00:37:49','2010-12-31 00:37:49','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=62',1,'nav_menu_item','',0),(68,2,'2010-12-31 00:53:24','2010-12-31 00:53:24','<h1>Mission</h1>\r\nIACT’s mission is to create engaging workshops, competitions, and related events to catalyze collaboration between businesses, researchers, and physicians in Pittsburgh. Its end goal is to spur technology innovation within healthcare and improve the region’s economy.\r\n<h1>History</h1>\r\nIACT was conceived in August 2010 with the vision of improving the world through healthcare       innovation. This vision quickly turned into a passion as the founders, students at the Tepper       School of Business at Carnegie Mellon, Carnegie Mellon Engineering, and the School of Medicine        at the University of Pittsburgh, began to explore the immense amount of healthcare talent       unique to Pittsburgh.\r\n\r\nThe mentorship of Jim \"Oz\" Osborn proved to be the spark that catapulted IACT from dream to       reality and provided inspiration for the first topic: Healthcare Technologies for an Aging America. Since its creation in July 2010, IACT has delivered two events on the topic “Healthcare Technologies for an Aging,” – an evening workshop and day-long student pitch competition. The first event brought together over 50 professionals and students in Pittsburgh to network, learn from local experts, and create marketable technologies. At the student pitch competition, called the Innovator’s Challenge, nearly 30 students competed for prizes by delivering the best pitch of a technology to improve the lives of older adults.\r\n\r\nIACT is delivering a similar evening workshop and student pitch competition on the topic of “Surgical Technology Innovation.” These events lay the groundwork for a long-term summer experience where students will create ventures with strong professional advising.\r\n\r\nIACT receives regular sponsorship from multiple institutions at local Pittsburgh universities. At Carnegie Mellon University, sponsors include the Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship at the Tepper School of Business, the Quality of Life Technology Center and Project Olympus. At the University of Pittsburgh, sponsors include the Office of Enterprise Development, the Institute of Entrepreneurship Excellence at the Katz School of Business and the Institute on Aging. From the Pittsburgh community at large, IACT has been working with the Pittsburgh Life Science Greenhouse to engage local leaders in the healthcare technology industry.\r\n<h1>Press Releases</h1>\r\nIACT\'s Workshop on \"Healthcare Technologies for an Aging America\"\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/IACT_Press_Release_11_9_10-external.pdf\">IACT_Press_Release_11_9_10</a>\r\n\r\nIACT\'s Innovator\'s Challenge on \"Healthcare Technologies for an Aging America\"\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/IACT-Innovators-Challenge-1.25.11-press-release.pdf\">IACT_Press_Release_1_25_11</a>\r\n\r\nIACT\'s Innovator\'s Forum on \"Technologies for Surgery\"\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/02/PressRelease_Surgery_2_25_11.pdf\">IACT_Press_Release_2_25_11</a>\r\n','About','','publish','closed','closed','','iact-about','','','2011-02-25 15:15:37','2011-02-25 20:15:37','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/',0,'page','',0),(74,2,'2010-12-31 00:53:51','2010-12-31 00:53:51','The mission of IACT is to create engaging workshops and events to foster  	  sustainable collaboration between industry, academics, and clinicians in  	  Pittsburgh to bring forward transformative       research and disruptive solutions within the healthcare field.\nHistory\nIACT was conceived in August 2010 with the vision of improving the world through healthcare       innovation. This vision quickly turned into a passion as the founders, students at the Tepper       School of Business at Carnegie Mellon, Carnegie Mellon Engineering, and the School of Medicine        at the University of Pittsburgh, began to explore the immense amount of healthcare talent       unique to Pittsburgh.\n\nThe mentorship of Jim “Oz” Osborn proved to be the spark that catapulted IACT from dream to       reality and provided inspiration for the first topic: Healthcare Technologies for an Aging America.       November 4, 2010 will mark the first event in IACT’s mission of creating a sustainable series       of workshops and events promoting healthcare technology collaboration between students and       professionals.','','','publish','open','open','','74','','','2010-12-31 00:53:51','2010-12-31 00:53:51','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=74',5,'nav_menu_item','',0),(75,2,'2010-12-31 01:10:33','2010-12-31 01:10:33','<h1>James Wolfe</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-225\" title=\"jameswolfe\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/jameswolfe.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"150\" />Mr. Wolfe is currently a Masters in Business Administration              student at Carnegie Mellon University’s Tepper School of Business.               His primary interest is healthcare technology entrepreneurship,              specifically in the areas of remote patient monitoring and medical              analytics.  For the past three years, Mr. Wolfe worked for Northrop              Grumman, Electronic Systems in engineering and manufacturing project              management.  He also co-founded Scratch Start, LLC in 2006 and managed              the development of the company’s first beauty aid product.  Mr. Wolfe              received a Graduate Certificate in Technical Management from Johns              Hopkins University in 2009.  He also holds a B.S. and M.S. in Mechanical              Engineering from Carnegie Mellon University and the University of California,              San Diego, respectively.\r\n<h1>Daniel Bishop</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-81\" title=\"danielbishop\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/danielbishop.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"151\" />Mr. Bishop graduated summa cum laude with his BS in Biomedical Engineering              from Arizona State University.  He was named the Outstanding Researcher of              his graduating class in the ASU Honors College for his work in the realm of              biosensors and bioanalytical chemistry. Applications of this research include              point-of-care diagnostics, on-body physiological sensors, and field-deployable              assays. He is now enrolled in the Medical Scientist Training Program where he              will complete his MD at the University of Pittsburgh and his PhD in Biomedical              Engineering at Carnegie Mellon University. He is currently performing research in              bioseparations for applications in biotechnology and medical diagnostics in the              lab of James Schneider in the CMU Department of Chemical Engineering. Other              academic ventures aim to improve the delivery of healthcare through engineering              solutions in the realms of quality control, healthcare IT, and infection control.              Broadly, he is interested in finding ways to catalyze healthcare innovation through              interdisciplinary collaboration.\r\n<h1>Jeffrey Mataya</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-85\" title=\"jeffmataya\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/jeffmataya.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"150\" />Mr. Mataya is currently a Masters in Business Administration             student at the Tepper School of Business at Carnegie Mellon             University.  He graduated in 2007 with his B.S. in Computer             Science from the University of Michigan.  For the past three years             he has worked as a software engineer at Microsoft as part of the             engineering team for products such as Windows Update.  More recently, he              ventured into the user interface space, where he earned Microsoft\'s Gold             Star Award for his work testing products in the IT space.\r\n\r\nHe is currently focusing on technology entrepreneurship with a particular             interest in innovative human-computer interaction and Internet-based             technologies within the healthcare industry.\r\n<h1>Jason Sanders</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-86\" title=\"jasonsanders\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/jasonsanders.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"150\" />Mr. Sanders was a University Scholar at Boston             University and graduated from its Honors Program in             2007 with a BA in biochemistry and molecular biology.             During his undergraduate years he pursued an interest             in public health by completing 2/3 of an MPH in             epidemiology. He then enrolled in the Medical             Scientist Training Program (MSTP) at the University             of Pittsburgh, which he plans to graduate from in             2014 with an MD and PhD in epidemiology. In the past             he conducted clinical and epidemiologic research on             genetic and environmental correlates of pediatric             infections and gender differences in lung cancer.             Now, he uses epidemiology to study the biology and             physiology of aging and longevity, air medical             transport for stroke care, and medical education.             Mr. Sanders was recently awarded a highly competitive             5-year pre-doctoral National Research Service Award to             study the epidemiology of lens aging.\r\n<h1>Megan LeJeune</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-89\" title=\"meganlejeune\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/meganlejeune.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"166\" />Megan LeJeune is a first-year MBA/Master of Health Care Policy and     		Management student at the Tepper School of Business and Heinz College 			of Carnegie Mellon.  She has previous experience in biomedical 			research (UPMC) and computational public health research (MIDAS), and 			is a co-author of multiple publications/pending publications.  She 			also spent some time in Marketing for Mosaic.  She co-founded a 			nonprofit, Butterfly Medical, dedicated to providing equitable access 			to health care information and innovation in Health IT in 2009, and 			launched a related summer internship program for students at the 			University of Pittsburgh shortly after.  She was awarded a Forte 			Fellowship to attend Carnegie Mellon University for graduate school, 			and had previously earned a Full-Tuition Academic Scholarship to the 			University of Pittsburgh, where she earned a B.S. in Molecular 			Biology.  Her current focus is in Marketing and Strategy, specifically 			in healthcare and science industries, and she is enthusiastic to help 			provide a launch-pad for innovative and integrative health care 			solutions via IACT.\r\n<h1>Mithun Neral</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-90\" title=\"mithunneral\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/mithunneral.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"150\" />Mr. Neral is currently pursuing his MD at the University of Pittsburgh. He attended the University of Michigan as a Siemens Scholar and Carlos and Gloria Wille Bell Scholar and graduated in 2010 with his B.S. in Biomedical Engineering, having a concentration in biomechanical engineering. Mithun worked in the Cardiovascular Research Center under Dr. David Pinsky from 2006 to 2010 where he explored the ectoenzymatic suppression of atherogenesis by CD39 as well as the regulation of CD39 expression by hemodynamic shear stress on endothelium. Interested in creating technological innovations to improve healthcare, Mithun is currently examining the potentially improved diagnostic capability of a screening test for carpal tunnel syndrome using a hand dynamometer.\r\n<h1>James Fisher</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-87\" title=\"jamesfisher\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/jamesfisher.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"153\" />James Fisher is a Pittsburgh native who graduated from the University of  Pittsburgh magna cum laude with a BS in Chemical and Petroleum  Engineering.  As an undergraduate Mr. Fisher conducted research for  three years in the McGowan Institute for Regenerative Medicine’s Medical  Devices Laboratory where he worked to develop an extracorporeal  hemoadsorption device aimed to treat sepsis.  Mr. Fisher was also  awarded the Western Pennsylvania American Institute for Chemical  Engineering (AIChE) Professional Promise Award.  Currently, Mr. Fisher  is enrolled in an NIH sponsored Medical Scientist Training Program where  he will complete his MD at the University of Pittsburgh and his PhD  also at the University of Pittsburgh in Chemical Engineering.  In  addition to this dual degree program, Mr. Fisher conducts work as a  clinical biomedical engineer for the University of Pittsburgh Medical  Center’s Artificial Heart Program where he is responsible for the  management of all patients supported on Ventricular Assist Devices  within the UPMC health system.  From a research standpoint Mr. Fisher is  interested in regenerative medicine, drug delivery and biomimetics;  clinically he wishes to pursue a career in surgery.\r\n<h1>Justin G Shaka</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-88\" title=\"justinshaka\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/justinshaka.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"158\" />Mr. Shaka has served as Chief Operating Officer of             REBIScan, a medical device firm specializing in             amblyopia technology, since its inception in 2009.             He serves as the Principal Investigator to a Phase I             SBIR award from the NIH, and is working closely with             FDA and hospital investigators to obtain approval for             the use of a pediatric ophthalmic device. In              addition, Mr. Shaka also brings four years experience             managing a $15 million sponsored-research budget,             as well as a $10 million charitable endowment, at             Children\'s Hospital Boston, a teaching affiliate of             Harvard Medical School.\r\n\r\nMr. Shaka will be graduating with an MBA from             Carnegie Mellon University, as a Schwartz Fellow in             biotechnology entrepreneurship, in 2011. He graduated             Phi Beta Kappa from the University of New Hampshire             in 2004.\r\n\r\n<h1>Kawa Shwaish</h1>\r\n\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-88\" title=\"justinshaka\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/kawashwaish.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"158\" />Mr. Shwaish is currently a Dual Masters Degree student completing a Master in Business Administration and a Master in the Management of Information Systems at the University of Pittsburgh Katz Graduate School of Business. He is particularly interested in improving Human Machine Interaction in healthcare by utilizing human-centric design methodology.  Mr. Shwaish worked as an Information Technology Manager and lead many healthcare IT projects with a focus on human-centric design methodology, systems integrations, and change management. He was a HIPAA officer and has over ten years of experience in Information Technology, eight of which were in the healthcare arena. He worked as an executive consultant and founded Innovation Beans LLC to bring the brightest students together and help them take their ideas to commercialization. He also holds a B.S. in Developmental Psychology and is an avid Artist. ','Student Board','','publish','closed','closed','','board','','','2011-03-08 17:52:40','2011-03-08 22:52:40','',0,'http://localhost/wordpress/',0,'page','',0),(93,2,'2010-12-31 01:11:10','2010-12-31 01:11:10','James Wolfe\nMr. Wolfe is currently a Master