s at the 			University of Pittsburgh shortly after.  She was awarded a Forte 			Fellowship to attend Carnegie Mellon University for graduate school, 			and had previously earned a Full-Tuition Academic Scholarship to the 			University of Pittsburgh, where she earned a B.S. in Molecular 			Biology.  Her current focus is in Marketing and Strategy, specifically 			in healthcare and science industries, and she is enthusiastic to help 			provide a launch-pad for innovative and integrative health care 			solutions via IACT.\n<h1>Mithun Neral</h1>\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-90\" title=\"mithunneral\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/mithunneral.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"150\" />Mr. Neral is currently pursuing his MD at the University of Pittsburgh. He attended the University of Michigan as a Siemens Scholar and Carlos and Gloria Wille Bell Scholar and graduated in 2010 with his B.S. in Biomedical Engineering, having a concentration in biomechanical engineering. Mithun worked in the Cardiovascular Research Center under Dr. David Pinsky from 2006 to 2010 where he explored the ectoenzymatic suppression of atherogenesis by CD39 as well as the regulation of CD39 expression by hemodynamic shear stress on endothelium. Interested in creating technological innovations to improve healthcare, Mithun is currently examining the potentially improved diagnostic capability of a screening test for carpal tunnel syndrome using a hand dynamometer.\n<h1>James Fisher</h1>\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-87\" title=\"jamesfisher\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/jamesfisher.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"153\" />James Fisher is a Pittsburgh native who graduated from the University of  Pittsburgh magna cum laude with a BS in Chemical and Petroleum  Engineering.  As an undergraduate Mr. Fisher conducted research for  three years in the McGowan Institute for Regenerative Medicine’s Medi