nterest             in public health by completing 2/3 of an MPH in             epidemiology. He then enrolled in the Medical             Scientist Training Program (MSTP) at the University             of Pittsburgh, which he plans to graduate from in             2014 with an MD and PhD in epidemiology. In the past             he conducted clinical and epidemiologic research on             genetic and environmental correlates of pediatric             infections and gender differences in lung cancer.             Now, he uses epidemiology to study the biology and             physiology of aging and longevity, air medical             transport for stroke care, and medical education.             Mr. Sanders was recently awarded a highly competitive             5-year pre-doctoral National Research Service Award to             study the epidemiology of lens aging.\r\n<h1>Megan LeJeune</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-89\" title=\"meganlejeune\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/meganlejeune.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"166\" />Megan LeJeune is a first-year MBA/Master of Health Care Policy and     		Management student at the Tepper School of Business and Heinz College 			of Carnegie Mellon.  She has previous experience in biomedical 			research (UPMC) and computational public health research (MIDAS), and 			is a co-author of multiple publications/pending publications.  She 			also spent some time in Marketing for Mosaic.  She co-founded a 			nonprofit, Butterfly Medical, dedicated to providing equitable access 			to health care information and innovation in Health IT in 2009, and 			launched a related summer internship program for students at the 			University of Pittsburgh shortly after.  She was awarded a Forte 			Fellowship to attend Carnegie Mellon University for graduate school, 			and had previously earned a Full-Tuition Academic Scholarship to the 			University of Pittsburgh, where she earned a B.S. in Molecular 			Biology.  Her current focus is in Marketing and Strategy, specifically 			in healthcare and science industries, and she is enthusiastic to help 			provide a launch-pad for innovative and integrative health care 			solutions via IACT.\r\n<h1>Mithun Neral</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-90\" title=\"mithunneral\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/mithunneral.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"150\" />Mr. Neral is currently pursuing his MD at the University of Pittsburgh. He attended the University of Michigan as a Siemens Scholar and Carlos and Gloria Wille Bell Scholar and graduated in 2010 with his B.S. in Biomedical Engineering, having a concentration in biomechanical engineering. Mithun worked in the Cardiovascular Research Center under Dr. David Pinsky from 2006 to 2010 where he explored the ectoenzymatic suppression of atherogenesis by CD39 as well as the regulation of CD39 expression by hemodynamic shear stress on endothelium. Interested in creating technological innovations to improve healthcare, Mithun is currently examining the potentially improved diagnostic capability of a screening test for carpal tunnel syndrome using a hand dynamometer.\r\n<h1>James Fisher</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-87\" title=\"jamesfisher\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/jamesfisher.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"153\" />James Fisher is a Pittsburgh native who graduated from the University of  Pittsburgh magna cum laude with a BS in Chemical and Petroleum  Engineering.  As an undergraduate Mr. Fisher conducted research for  three years in the McGowan Institute for Regenerative Medicine’s Medical  Devices Laboratory where he worked to develop an extracorporeal  hemoadsorption device aimed to treat sepsis.  Mr. Fisher was also  awarded the Western Pennsylvania American Institute for Chemical  Engineering (AIChE) Professional Promise Award.  Currently, Mr. Fisher  is enrolled in an NIH sponsored Medical Scientist Training Program where  he will complete his MD at the University of Pittsburgh and his PhD  also at the University of Pittsburgh in Chemical Engineering.  In  addition to this dual degree program, Mr. Fisher conducts work as a  clinical biomedical engineer for the University of Pittsburgh Medical  Center’s Artificial Heart Program where he is responsible for the  management of all patients supported on Ventricular Assist Devices  within the UPMC health system.  From a research standpoint Mr. Fisher is  interested in regenerative medicine, drug delivery and biomimetics;  clinically he wishes to pursue a career in surgery.\r\n<h1>Justin G Shaka</h1>\r\n<img id=\"bioPic\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-88\" title=\"justinshaka\" src=\"http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/justinshaka.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"113\" height=\"158\" />Mr. Shaka has served as Chief Operating Officer of             REBIScan, a medical device firm specializing in             amblyopia technology, since its inception in 2009.             He serves as the Principal Investigator to a Phase I             SBIR award from the NIH, and is working closely with             FDA and hospital investigators to obtain approval for             the use of a pediatric ophthalmic device. In              addition, Mr. Shaka also brings four years experience             managing a $15 million sponsored-research budget,             as well as a $10 million charitable endowment, at             Children\'s Hospital Boston, a teaching affiliate of             Harvard Medical School.\r\n\r\nMr. Shaka will be graduating with an MBA from             Carnegie Mellon University, as a Schwartz Fellow in             biotechnology entrepreneurship, in 2011. He graduated             Phi Beta Kappa from the University of New Hampshire             in 2004.','Student Board','','inherit','open','open','','75-revision-3','','','2011-01-15 13:26:59','2011-01-15 18:26:59','',75,'http://iactpgh.com/uncategorized/75-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(238,1,'2011-01-15 16:38:38','2011-01-15 21:38:38','The IACT Difference\r\nIACT workshops are hight-impact, collaborative experiences bringing together students and healthcare professionals from across the Pittsburgh area.\r\n\r\nEach IACT workshop is unique and tackles the most challenging problems in healthcare.\r\nFormat\r\nWorkshops are three hours long and follow a dedicated format:\r\n\r\n	Keynote speaker from a leader within the sector5\r\n	Panel discussion with experts from industry academia, and clinical medicine.\r\n	Collaborative breakout sessions addressing key themes based on the workshop’s focus.\r\n\r\nExpert Panel\r\nThe evening will continue with a panel of experts from within the healthcare industry, academia,       and clinical research who will discuss the challenges and opportunities facing the field.\r\nBreakout Sessions\r\nBreakout sessions form the bulk of the IACT experience, allowing students and professionals       to brainstorm solutions, learn about cutting edge research and businesses, and build lasting       relationships that will lead to tomorrow’s fundable opportunities.','Discover Why IACT is Unique','','publish','open','open','','discover-why-iact-is-unique','','','2011-01-26 20:13:45','2011-01-27 01:13:45','',0,'http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/?p=238',2,'nav_menu_item','',0),(309,1,'2011-01-26 20:13:45','2011-01-27 01:13:45','Past IACT Events\r\nBelow is the brief history of IACT events. Please feel free to explore!\r\n\r\nIACT Workshop: Healthcare Technologies for an Aging America\r\n\r\nThe first ever IACT workshop! See all of the great content here.\r\n\r\nIACT Innovator’s Challenge: Healthcare Technologies for an Aging America\r\n\r\nThe first Innovator’s Challenge has just completed! Stay tuned for the exciting content. In the meantime, learn what the event was about here.\r\n\r\n','Explore Past Events','','publish','open','open','','explore-past-events-3','','','2011-01-26 20:13:45','2011-01-27 01:13:45','',0,'http://iactpgh.com/?p=309',1,'nav_menu_item','',0),(240,1,'2011-01-15 16:40:15','2011-01-15 21:40:15','Healthcare Technologies for an Aging America\r\nThe November 4th event was a huge success! Please explore all of the ideas that came out of the event.\r\n\r\nAlso, be sure to check out videos of the event’s sponsors and featured attendees! Links are in the sidebar to the right.\r\nInnovation Teams\r\n\r\n[widgets_on_pages id=1]','Event Home','','publish','open','open','','event-home-2','','','2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','',0,'http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/?p=240',1,'nav_menu_item','',0),(241,1,'2011-01-15 16:40:15','2011-01-15 21:40:15','Healthcare Technologies for an Aging America\r\nThe first IACT event will be help on November 4, 2010 at Newell Simon Hall, Room 3305. We are set for an evening of networking and brainstorming as we prepare to revolutionize healthcare technologies.\r\nMeet the Featured Speakers\r\nFeatured Keynote Speaker\r\nJim Osborn, Executive Director of the Quality of Life Technology Center, University of Pittsburgh and Carnegie Mellon University\r\nFeatured Panelists\r\nArthur Boni, Ph.D. – Director of the Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship, Carnegie Mellon University\r\n\r\nCharles F. Reynolds III, M.D. – UPMC Endowed Professor in Geriatric Psychiatry; Directory, Aging Institute of University of Pittsburgh and UPMC\r\n\r\nJay Srini – Chief Strategist, SCS Ventures\r\nDiscover the IACT Vision!\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q5fc3nJKi8Y&feature=player_embedded\r\nLearn more about IACT and see more exclusive videos here!','Event Preview','','publish','open','open','','event-preview-2','','','2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','',114,'http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/?p=241',2,'nav_menu_item','',0),(242,1,'2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','IACT Keynote Speaker: Jim “Oz” Osborn\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-PnvXZKNAmI&feature=player_embedded','','','publish','open','open','','242','','','2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','',114,'http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/?p=242',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(243,1,'2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','Featured Panelist: Arthur Boni, Ph.D.\r\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P5uLro588vo&feature=player_embedded\r\nArthur A. Boni, Ph. D. has held the John R. Thorne Chair of Entrepreneurship at the Tepper School of Business at Carnegie Mellon University since 2003, and is the Director of the Donald H. Jones Center for Entrepreneurship. He teaches undergraduates, MBAs and executives in emerging companies. His teaching and research interests include: entrepreneurship and new venture creation, commercialization of technology and biotechnology, venture capital investing, innovation and entrepreneurship in organizations, leadership and broad-based ownership in entrepreneurial companies, and biopharmaceutical and alternative energy industries.\r\n\r\nDr. Boni has spent most of his career as an entrepreneur in technology and life science companies in San Diego, CA and Boston, MA. His entrepreneurial career started with Science Applications International Corporation (SAIC) which initiated his long held interest in the power of broad-based company ownership. He joined the company after its startup period and became part of the senior management team that built the company to the $600 million level, exiting as a Senior Vice President. SAIC has grown to an approximately $11 billion annual revenue technology conglomerate, was the country’s largest employee owned technology company, and then successfully completed an IPO in October, 2006. He then founded and served as CEO of a technology incubator in the greater Boston area, and led the formation, development stages, and financing of four companies that focused on minimally invasive medical devices, life science software, pharmaceutical therapeutic development, and electro-optic process monitoring and control.\r\n\r\nDr. Boni also founded and managed the Office of Technology Management at the University of Pittsburgh where he managed the commercialization of technologies for the university and its medical school including IP, licensing and company formation. Dr. Boni was also a founding partner of Saturn Life Science Partners LLC, a venture capital organization.\r\n\r\nDr. Boni’s educational background includes a BS from Carnegie Mellon University (Mechanical Engineering), MS from the University of Southern California (Mechanical Engineering), and a Ph. D. from the University of California, San Diego (Engineering Science/Engineering Physics). He served as an Assistant Professor in the Department of Engineering and Applied Science at Yale University and has over 80 open literature publications.','','','publish','open','open','','243','','','2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','',114,'http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/?p=243',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(244,1,'2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','IACT Featured Panelist: Charles F. Reynolds III, M.D.\r\nCharles F. Reynolds III, M.D., is the UPMC Endowed Professor in Geriatric Psychiatry at the University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine. He serves as Director for the Aging Institute of UPMC Senior Services and of the University of Pittsburgh. In addition, he directs the Advanced Center for Interventions and Services Research for Late-Life Mood Disorders the Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic, the John A. Hartford Center of Excellence in Geriatric Psychiatry and two NIMH-funded Research Training Grants.\r\n\r\nDr. Reynolds is internationally renowned in the field of geriatric psychiatry. His primary research interests focus on mood and sleep disorders of later life, with a particular focus on treatment (including mental health services in primary care, the mechanisms of treatment response, preventive interventions and suicide prevention.)\r\n\r\nDr. Reynolds graduated magna cum laude from the University of Virginia before earning his medical degree from Yale University School of Medicine in 1973. He then completed a straight medical internship at the Royal Victoria Hospital and Montreal Neurological Hospital and continued on to post-graduate work in adult and geriatric psychiatry, sleep disorders and clinical electroencephalography at the Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic.\r\n\r\nThe recipient of a National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH) Research Scientist Award and a MERIT award for Maintenance Therapies in Late-Life Depression, Dr. Reynolds has twice been named one of The Best Doctors in America. Dr. Reynolds chaired the planning committee for the 1991 NIH consensus development conference on the Diagnosis and Treatment of Depression in Late-Life and the 2001 NDMDA consensus conference on Unmet Needs in the Diagnosis and Treatment of Late-Life Mood Disorder. In addition to serving on the Institute of Medicine Study of the Pathophysiology and Prevention of Adolescent and Adult Suicide, Dr. Reynolds has served as chairman and member of several research review committees at the NIMH. He has been a member of the National Advisory Mental Health Council of the NIMH and has served as President of the American College of Psychiatrists and the International College of Geriatric Psychoneuropharmacology.\r\n\r\nDr. Reynolds’ bibliography contains over 500 publications in peer-reviewed journals, which he has written over the past 31 years. The associate editor of American Journal of Geriatric Psychiatry, Dr. Reynolds has also served on the editorial board of several neuropsychiatric, gerontology and sleep journals including the Archives of General Psychiatry, the American Journal of Psychiatry and Neuropsychopharmacology.','','','publish','open','open','','244','','','2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','',114,'http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/?p=244',5,'nav_menu_item','',0),(245,1,'2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','IACT Featured Panelist: Jay Srini\r\nJay Srini is currently serving as the Chief Strategist at SCS Ventures where she is working with startup companies internationally to help them with their business development, technology strategy and expansion. The business models for the client companies range from e-health to personal health management, and telemedicine. Jay’s prior experience includes her role as Chief Innovation Officer for UPMC (University of Pittsburgh Medical Center) Insurance Services Division as well as her role as Vice President of Emerging Technologies for UPMC. Her responsibilities as VP of Emerging Technologies included providing strategic direction and input regarding emerging technologies and solutions to University of Pittsburgh Medical Center and their Insurances subsidiary. Jay was Managing Director for e-Health Initiatives at Internet Venture Works where she led technology and industry assessments of opportunities presented by strategic partners, investors and external sources and served in interim executive management roles for its’ portfolio companies before joining UPMC as VP of Emerging Technologies.\r\n\r\nJay has a Master’s Degree in Computer Science from New York University and a Master’s Degree in Business Administration from Bucknell University and her executive education from the Kellogg School of Management at Northwestern University. She also serves on the advisory board of several entrepreneurial companies, nonprofit healthcare organizations and serves as one of the commissioners at CCHIT (Certification Commission of HealthCare Information Technology) in addition to her role as adjunct faculty at the University of Pittsburgh.','','','publish','open','open','','245','','','2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','',114,'http://iactpgh.com/test/wordpress/?p=245',6,'nav_menu_item','',0),(246,1,'2011-01-15 16:41:42','2011-01-15 21:41:42','Driving Directions to Campus\r\nClick to download the Carnegie 